\begin_layout Section
pcp_combine options with lat-lon grid data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than converting to GRIB1 use the wgrib2 utility to do the regridding:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
gfsrain06.grb is a GRIB2 file on a global lat/lon grid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
wgrib2 gfsrain06.grb -new_grid latlon 112:131:0.1 25:121:0.1 gfsrain06_regrid.grb2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And then run that GRIB2 file through pcp_combine:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
pcp_combine -add gfsrain06_regrid.grb2 'name="APCP"; level="A6";' gfsrain06_regri
d.nc
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the output NetCDF file does not have this problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
ncdump -h 2a_wgrib2_regrid.nc | grep "_ll"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
:lat_ll = "25.000000 degrees_north" ;
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
:lon_ll = "112.000000 degrees_east" ;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MET can read both GRIB1 and GRIB2 data.
 Also, MET version 5.2 includes an automated regridding feature.
 So the data can pass to grid_stat on different grids...
 and instruct grid_stat to regrid one to the other.
 That would avoid the need to do regridding using copygb or wgrib2 at all.
\end_layout

